review_comments.body:
yes @dougwilson, you are right here for a high volume of data I used [`Writablestream`](https://nodejs.org/dist/latest-v20.x/docs/api/webstreams.html#class-writablestream) to achieve better control over this  
```javascript 
var WritableStream = require('stream/web').WritableStream;
        blob.stream().pipeTo(new WritableStream({
          write: function (chunk) {
            _this.write(chunk);
          },
          close: function () {
            _this.end();
          }
        }))
```

that solution was just to give you a rough estimate on what you actually have to do logic wise - reading part of a blob and return something iterable that keeps reading little by little.  not how to actually write a complete example in old school code. i left out a hole lot in that code example like the `function` signature, where it gets the blob from how it uses `stream.Readable.from()`

it's 100% compatible to write a old-style iterable function that simply just returns a object and having a single Symbol.iterator symbol.

here is a mdn example of creating a iterable. just had to make a sligh adjustment to say that it should return a object with a symbol.iterator instead
```js
function makeRangeIterator(start = 0, end = Infinity, step = 1) {
  let nextIndex = start;
  let iterationCount = 0;

  const rangeIterator = {
    next() {
      let result;
      if (nextIndex < end) {
        result = { value: nextIndex, done: false };
        nextIndex += step;
        iterationCount++;
        return result;
      }
      return { value: iterationCount, done: true };
    },
  }
  const obj = {}
  obj[Symbol.iterator] = function() {
    return rangeIterator
  }
  return obj;
}

[...makeRangeIterator(0, 10)] // 0, 1, 2 ... 10
```
As you can see this dose not use any generator or `yield` stuff. it's enough that you have a object that has a `symbol.toIterator` that returns a simple object that has `{ next() { ... }}` which in upon calling should return a `{ value, done }` object for it to be acceptable by `stream.Readable.from(iterable)` the only thing left is change things to `var` instead.

i just didn't feel like writing a hole such example of reading blobs little by little using a own custom iterable function would be necessary, cuz i don't think it should be included anyway. but if you like me too do it then i could. 

anyway. i'm going to mark this message as of topic. as v5.x don't seem to have the same restriction anymore

now you actually made me want to show of using older syntax just for the sake of it 😜 

```js
/**
 * Read a blob little by little using .arrayBuffer() and slice()
 * @param {Blob} blob 
 * @param {number} chunkSize
 * @returns and iterable object
 */
function streamBlob(blob, chunkSize = 1024) {
  var offset = 0

  var iterator = {
    next() {
      return new Promise(function (resolve, reject) {
        var chunk = blob.slice(offset, offset + chunkSize)
        
        return chunk.text().then(function text) {
          resolve({
            value: text,
            done: offset >= blob.size
          })

          offset += chunkSize
        })
      })
    }
  }
  
  var obj = {}
  obj[Symbol.asyncIterator] = function () {
    return iterator
  }

  return obj
}

// To show that it's now iterable:
const blob = new Blob(['hello world'])
const iterable = streamBlob(blob, 2)

for await (const chunk of iterable) {
  console.log(chunk)
}
```
might just still have to get rid of the optional chunkSize argument and change it to resolve with a Uint8Array instead of a string (text) just wanted to use it cuz it's more for demo purpose

